article.description: Tamika Whitmore scored 22 points to lead the Fever to a 74-67 victory over Washington, ending the Mystics' seven-game home winning streak.
article.headline: Whitmore's 22 points lead Fever past Mystics
article.linkText: Whitmore's 22 points lead Fever past Mystics
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Tamika Whitmore rebounded from her worst offensive game of the season to help Indiana end Washington's nine-game home winning streak.

Whitmore scored 11 of her 22 points in the fourth quarter to lead the Fever to a 74-67 victory over the Mystics on Tuesday night. On Sunday, she managed only two points on 0-for-6 shooting in 25 minutes in an 82-61 loss at Sacramento.

"I don't look to come out and score points every night, I just look to do the little things that help us win," said Whitmore, who shot 9-for-16 from the field. "They had a box-and-one on [Tamika] Catchings and double-teamed her all the time, and everybody just stepped up."

Whitmore's intensity level increased after Catchings was floored by an elbow to the face courtesy of Mystics center Chasity Melvin with 7:36 left in the second quarter.

"That made me angry because I thought it was unnecessary," Whitmore said. "It's just one of those feelings where you don't want to lose. We just didn't want a repeat of Sacramento."

It took a while for Catchings to regain feeling in her face.

"I'm a little dented on this side, but it's cool," said Catchings, who had 15 points, including a 3-pointer with 1:09 remaining, and five rebounds. "I hate getting hit in the face. It's one of my worst pet peeves. My nose was the first one and I got hit on this side in the fourth quarter, but it's all good.

"We stuck together and played well together. Even though they were doing a box-and-one, the group that went in when I was sitting on the bench did a great job."

Washington entered the game 7-0 at the Verizon Center this year after winning its last two games at home last season.

The Fever (11-5) sealed the victory by making 10 of 12 free throws in the final 37.8 seconds.

Alana Beard had 24 points, matched her career-high with 10 rebounds, and distributed five assists for the Mystics (8-6), who erased a 16-point first-half deficit.

"It's pretty painful, actually, simply because we know that we could've won the game," said Beard, who shot 11-for-14 from the field.

The Fever made six of their first 11 shots and took an early 17-4 lead while the Mystics opened with 2-for-8 shooting and five turnovers. Catchings' second 3-pointer of the game extended Indiana's lead to 20-4 with 1:40 remaining in the first quarter.

Nikki Teasley had 13 points and seven assists for Washington. Crystal Robinson added 12 points.

Tan White's 3-pointer gave Indiana a 51-48 lead with 5:42 left and the Fever led the rest of the way.

Coco Miller's breakaway layup gave Washington its first lead at 39-38 with 3:01 remaining in the third quarter.

Indiana played its fifth game without forward Charlotte Smith, whose father died recently.
